Package cmpt355.project.ast.node

Class AstNode

java.lang.Object
cmpt355.project.ast.node.AstNode
Direct Known Subclasses:
ClassDefinition, DataTypeNode, Expression, FieldDeclaration, Import, JavaFile, MethodDefinition, Statement, Variable
public abstract class AstNode
extends Object
Abstract base class for abstract syntax tree nodes. Defines some utility methods for AST traversal. Subclasses of AstNode override children() so that the AST can be traversed.

Important note: since many kinds of AST nodes need to be able to climb the tree (towards the root) — for example, a node representing reference to a variable will need to find the declaration to that variable in an enclosing scope to determine its data type — it is very important that every AstNode has its parent node set. The recommended way to do this is to use the reparent(AstNode) and related methods, for example


     public class WhileLoop extends Statement {

         private Expression condition;

         public void setCondition(Expression condition) {
             this.condition = reparentNonNull(condition);
         }
     }

(reparentNonNull(AstNode) calls setParentNode(AstNode) and throws an exception if the argument is null, making sure that the parent is set and that the argument to setCondition() was not null simultaneously.)

  • Method Details

    • validateType

      public void validateType() throws DataTypeException
      Typechecks this AST node, ensuring that data types are used correctly in it. The default version does nothing; subclasses of AstNode should override this method if they have anything to do with data types. This method should only be called on a node after it has been called on all of the node's children. In other words this method should be called in a post-order traversal.
      Throws:
      DataTypeException - if there is a data type error involving this node

    • getParentNode

      public AstNode getParentNode()
      Returns the parent node of this AstNode, or null if the node has no parent. (By the time the AST is done being built, the only node with no parent should be the root [see the note at the top of the class about parent nodes].)

    • setParentNode

      public void setParentNode​(AstNode parentNode)
      Sets the parent node of this node. Every AstNode except the root should have its parent set.

    • findVariable

      public Optional<? extends Variable> findVariable​(String varName)
      Convenience method to look up a variable from all symbol holder parents of this node. Returns the variable found from the closest ancestor SymbolHolder node, or an empty Optional if not found.

    • findClass

      public Optional<? extends ClassType> findClass​(String className)
      Convenience method to look up a class type from all symbol holder parents of this node. Returns the class found from the closest ancestor SymbolHolder node, or an empty Optional if not found.

    • reparent

      protected <N extends AstNode> N reparent​(N node)
      Convenience method to be used by AstNode subclasses: if node is non-null, set its parent to this. Either way, return it. Equivalent to 
      
     if (node != null)
         node.setParentNode(this);
     return node;
      Type Parameters:
      N - the type of the node being set (so that the return type of reparent() is the same as whatever node was given so casts are not necessary)
      Parameters:
      node - the node to set the parent of
      Returns:
      the same node (after setting its parent)

    • reparent

      protected <N extends AstNode,​ L extends List<? extends N>> L reparent​(L list)
      Convenience method to be used by AstNode subclasses: if list is non-null, set each node it contains to this; either way, return it. Equivalent to 
      
     if (list != null)
         list.forEach(elem -> elem.setParentNode(this));
     return list;
      Type Parameters:
      N - the type of the elements of list
      L - the type of the list
      Parameters:
      list - a list of nodes to set the parent of
      Returns:
      the same list (after setting parent of each element)

    • children

      public List<? extends AstNode> children()
      Returns a list of all AstNode children of this node. (The List.of() and Lists.builder() methods are convenient ways to create such lists.)

      Please note that tree traversal is performed by calling this method on nodes of the AST; therefore any node not included in its parent's children() is effectively not in the AST.

    • findAncestor

      public <N> Optional<N> findAncestor​(Predicate<? super AstNode> predicate)
      Returns the first ancestor node of this node for which the predicate returns true. For example, node.findAncestor(n -> n instanceof Statement) will return the first ancestor that is a Statement, or an empty Optional if there is no such ancestor.
      Type Parameters:
      N - type of the value returned in the optional, so that code such as Optional<Optional> stmt = node.findAncestor(n -> n instanceof Statement); is allowed
      Parameters:
      predicate -
      Returns:
      an Optional containing the nearest ancestor matching the predicate, or an empty Optional if there is no such ancestor

    • toString

      public abstract String toString()
      Returns a String representation of this node. This method is declared abstract in AstNode to force subclasses to implement it.
      Overrides:
